# Test the real product, never substitute assertions for looking

A green automated test suite proves the code paths you wrote
assertions for behaved as you expected. It does **not** prove the
operator can read the screen, reach the control, or complete the
task. When a change touches a user-facing surface, or the user
asked you to verify / test / exercise something, you must drive the
**real built-and-deployed product** and **observe the actual result
with your own eyes** — a screen capture you actually read, a file you
actually open, a command output you actually read.

This rule has `alwaysApply: true` because the failure mode is
invisible until an operator hits it: the agent reports "done, tests
pass," the operator launches the app, and the UI is unusable.

## The rule

> **For any change to a user-facing surface (GUI dialog, web page,
> CLI output, an operator-opened file) — or any time the user asks
> you to verify / test / confirm something — you must (1) exercise
> the REAL deployed artifact under test, (2) capture and actually
> READ the visible result, and (3) operate every control / element
> the user named and every one the change touches. "N/N automated
> assertions pass" is necessary but is NEVER, by itself, evidence
> that the surface works. Existence is not operability.**

## Required steps before claiming a UI / verification task is done

1. **Identify the real artifact under test.** The installed binary
   under `C:\Program Files\AIC\…`, the running operator URL, or the
   deployed file — never `target\release\…`, never a mock, never the
   source. Deploy first per
   [`deploy-verify-after-desktop-or-web-fix.mdc`](deploy-verify-after-desktop-or-web-fix.mdc).
2. **Capture the visible state and read it.** For a window or page,
   take a screenshot of the running surface and inspect the image.
   Use the per-product capture script when one exists (for example
   `pim-offline-client-elevate-win32/scripts/capture-elevate-ui.ps1`).
   Look for: clipped controls, off-screen / below-the-fold fields,
   overlapping labels, unexpected default focus or auto-selection,
   missing scroll, and window sizing relative to the monitor work
   area.
3. **Operate every control the user named and every one the change
   touches.** Type into inputs, toggle checkboxes, click buttons,
   then read the resulting status / end state — confirm the outcome,
   not merely that a call returned `Ok` or that the element exists.
   For CLI / file changes, run the command or open the file and read
   the bytes.
4. **Exercise the SPECIFIC scope the user requested.** If the user
   said "confirm the new design and all controls operate," visually
   confirm the redesign renders AND drive each control — do not
   silently narrow it to a convenient subset.
5. **Re-check at the product's stress presets.** Large font, 200 %
   zoom, smallest allowed window, longest realistic string. These
   expose layout collisions and clipping that fixed-default
   assertions never see.

## Forbidden

- Reporting "done" / "fixed" / "N/N tests pass" for a visual or
  user-facing change **without a screen capture (or rendered output)
  that you actually inspected**.
- Treating screen capture or manual operation as a "pending" or
  optional to-do **when the user explicitly asked for it**. If the
  user asked you to capture and test, that is a required gate, not a
  backlog item.
- Verifying against `target\release\`, a mock harness, the DOM
  snapshot alone, or the source tree instead of the deployed product
  an operator actually runs.
- Inferring a control "works" because a function returned `Ok`, an
  HTTP call returned 200, or an element is present in the dialog
  template / DOM. **Present ≠ visible ≠ reachable ≠ operable.**
- Letting a passing automated suite stand in for "I looked at it and
  operated it." Automated assertions are a floor, never the ceiling.

## Worked violation → fix (the failure that created this rule)

**Violation** (2026-06-13, `pim-offline-client-elevate-win32`):
40/40 Win32 Pester assertions passed — every control was present in
the dialog, the window clamped to its minimum track size — and the
redesign was reported "done." A single screen capture of the running
app then showed:

- the entire disclosure body auto-selected (blue) on launch,
- the **Confirm this request** checkbox clipped off the bottom edge,
  so the Submit button could never enable,
- the task fields (Local group, Duration, Activation code) hidden
  below the fold, invisible in the default view,
- controls overlapping at the Large-font preset.

Existence checks all passed; the product was unusable. The capture
script was already sitting in `scripts\` and would have caught every
one of these in one shot.

**Fix**: run the capture script against the deployed exe, read both
the default and Large-font images, operate the code field +
checkbox + submit, and only then report status — with the screenshots
as the evidence.

## Status-reply shape for a verified UI change

State the artifact you drove, the capture(s) you read, the controls
you operated and their end state, and the presets you checked:

> Drove `C:\Program Files\AIC\OfflinePimAgent\pim-offline-client-elevate-win32.exe`.
> Captured default + Large-font; both fit the work area, no clipping
> or overlap. Typed `ABCDEFGH` into the code field, checked Confirm,
> Submit enabled and returned "agent unreachable" status as expected.

If you could not capture / operate it (file lock, no display, missing
script), say so explicitly and do **not** claim the surface is
verified.

